A Tutorial to Genome Explorer in R

Kari Lavikka

Jun 7, 2017

This is a short tutorial to Genome Explorer, a JavaScipt library and R package for visualizing genomic coordinates. It is most conveniently used with RStudio and/or Shiny, but it also works with vanilla R.

Installation

The package is available in Anduril R repository. Installation is easy:

install.packages("GenomeExplorer", repos = "http://anduril.org/pub/R")

Or if you want to live on the bleeding edge:

devtools::install_github("tuner/genome-explorer")

Our first visualization

Let’s first import the library. We also use magrittr to conveniently add features to Genome Explorer by using the pipe %>% operator.

library(GenomeExplorer)
library(magrittr)

Here is an example with the minimum amount of data and no extra options of any kind. The data contains a single genomic region, which we visualize using the default simple visualization. Genome Explorer comes bundled with chromosome data (cytobands) for a few common genome assemblies. Here we use hg38.

By default, Genome Explorer expects to find chromosome, start coordinate, and end coordinate from chrom, start, and end columns, respectively.

data <- data.frame(
  chrom = c("chr5"),
  start = c(50000000),
  end = c(150000000)
)

GenomeExplorer("hg38") %>%
  segmentTrack(data)

A more advanced example

Our data now contais two new columns: patient and type.

##   patient chrom     start       end   type
## 1       A  chr5  50000000  70000000   high
## 2       A  chr5 100000000 120000000    low
## 3       B  chr5  50000000  70000000   high
## 4       B  chr7  50000000  70000000    low
## 5       C  chr8  50000000 120000000 medium
## 6       C  chr9 100000000 120000000    low

Genome Explorer can display several tracks concurrently, and each track may have a different dataset and visualization type. We will stick with just one track for now.

As we would like to compare the patients with one another, we use the patient column as a discriminator. Each patient then gets an own subtrack. Type is just an arbitrary column that we want to use for coloring the bars produced by the simple visualization.

GenomeExplorer("hg38") %>%
  segmentTrack(
    data,
    discriminator = "patient",
    vis = simpleVis(
      color = "type"
    )
  )

A complete example

We finally move on to a real use case. Our data now contains genomic ranges with copy number variation data. We have two variables: Seg (segment mean) and BAF (B Allele Frequency) values. Here’s a sample of the dataset:

##   case  Chr    Start       End    segMean    bafMean
## 1   D1 chr1    61735     62937 -2.2169701         NA
## 2   D1 chr1    72704  25583341 -0.4997449 0.07537458
## 3   D1 chr1 25593128  25646744 -2.9766163         NA
## 4   D1 chr1 25646946  54218080 -0.6063597 0.07379540
## 5   D1 chr1 54222571  54328487 -0.1377848 0.07379540
## 6   D1 chr1 54328814  72768498 -0.6471139 0.07442718
## 7   D1 chr1 72768916  72811904 -2.4994263         NA
## 8   D1 chr1 72812440 121482979 -0.6293465 0.07414550

The columns that define the genomic coordinates are now named differently. Fortunately, you do not need to rename the columns - just define them explicitly by attributes chrom, start, and end.

Because we would like to compare the diagnosis (D) and relapse (R) samples side by side, we explicitly enumerate the cases in a specific order. By default, they are ordered alphanumerically.

Genome Explorer provides you with a particular visualization (cnvVis) for CNV and BAF data. CNV, which is expressed as segment mean, is displayed as a color, ranging from blue (negative, deletion) to red (positive, amplification) through white (zero, no change). BAF is actually displayed as LOH (Loss of Heterozygosity), which is calculated using the formula: |baf - 0.5| * 2. The height of the bar is determined by LOH, 0% means full heterozygosity, 100% mean total loss of the B allele.

We also define a title for the data track. Looks prettier that way.

As a final touch we include a gene annotation track, which gives our data some context. The genes and transcripts become visible when you zoom in enough.

GenomeExplorer("hg19") %>%
  segmentTrack(
    data,
    
    # Define the columns for genomic coordinates
    chrom = "Chr",
    start = "Start",
    end = "End",
    
    discriminator = "case",
    
    samples = c("D1", "R1",
                "D2", "R2"),
    
    vis = cnvVis(
      # Define the columns. Defining both of them is not mandatory.
      seg = "segMean",
      baf = "bafMean"
    ),
    
    title = "CNV & LOH"
  ) %>%
  refseqGeneTrack()

Using in Shiny

Here is an example of a trivial Shiny app.

library(shiny)
library(GenomeExplorer)
library(magrittr)

ui <- basicPage(
  GenomeExplorerOutput("myExplorer"),
  verbatimTextOutput("info")
)

server <- function(input, output) {
  output$myExplorer <- renderGenomeExplorer({
    GenomeExplorer("hg38") %>%
      segmentTrack(data.frame(chrom = c("chr5"), start = c(50000000), end = c(150000000)))
  })
  
  output$info <- renderText({
    # Display the brushed range
    if (!is.null(input$myExplorer_brushed)) {
      with(input$myExplorer_brushed,
           sprintf("Brushed range: %s:%d - %s:%d", start$chrom, start$pos, end$chrom, end$pos))
    }
  })
}

shinyApp(ui, server)

GenomeExplorer communicates brushing (range selection) events back to Shiny and exposes the selection in the input variable outputId_brushed where outputId is the id that has been given to the component. In the example above it is myExplorer. The data structure is a two-level list or NULL if the selection was discarded:

list(
  start = list(chrom = "chr4", pos = 123456),
  end = list(chrom = "chr7", pos = 654321)
)
